40|$|Property <b>tax</b> <b>is</b> one of {{the most}} {{important}} tools of each state economics. Immovable property <b>tax</b> <b>is</b> imposed upon land, buildings and building spaces utilized for economic activity, except conditions determined by the law, as well as starting from 2010 the <b>tax</b> <b>was</b> imposed upon dwelling houses and engineering structures...|$|R
50|$|In China, {{the payroll}} <b>tax</b> <b>is</b> a {{specific}} <b>tax</b> which <b>is</b> paid to provinces and territories by employers, not by employees. The <b>tax</b> <b>is</b> deducted from the worker's pay. The Chinese Government itself requires only one <b>tax</b> to <b>be</b> withheld from paychecks: the PAYG (or pay-as-you-go) tax, which includes medicare levies.|$|R
50|$|Under the Soviet rule, the Lithuanian {{financial}} system, including <b>taxes,</b> <b>was</b> {{integrated into}} the Soviet one. The personal income <b>tax</b> <b>was</b> progressive and ranged from 0.35 to 13 percent on income above the non-taxable amount. Local <b>taxes</b> <b>were</b> also collected: house and land ownership tax, as well as vehicle ownership tax.|$|R
